<h2>FAQ</h2>
<p><strong>What is the difference between primary and secondary keywords?</strong></p>
<p>Primary keywords are the main target. Secondary keywords are related terms that support the primary keyword and expand reach.</p>
<p><strong>How many secondary keywords should I use?</strong></p>
<p>Use 5-15 secondary keywords per page, depending on content length. One per 200-300 words is a good guideline.</p>
<p><strong>Where should I place secondary keywords?</strong></p>
<p>Use them in headings, introduction, body content, image alt text, internal links, and conclusion. Do not force them.</p>
<p><strong>Can secondary keywords outrank the primary keyword?</strong></p>
<p>Yes. Sometimes a page ranks better for a secondary keyword than the primary. This is common and beneficial.</p>
<p><strong>Should I create separate pages for secondary keywords?</strong></p>
<p>Only if the secondary keyword has distinct search intent. If it is a subtopic, include it on the same page.</p>
<p><strong>How do I find secondary keywords?</strong></p>
<p>Use Google Related Searches, People Also Ask, keyword research tools, competitor analysis, and Google Search Console.</p>
<p><strong>Are LSI keywords the same as secondary keywords?</strong></p>
<p>No. LSI keywords are conceptually related terms. Secondary keywords are direct variations and subtopics. Use both.</p>
